{"title":"You Need Multiple Exiting: Dynamic Early Exiting for Accelerating Unified Vision Language Model","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Unified vision-language (encoder-decoder) models incur high inference cost and existing early-exit methods either target encoder-only models or only the decoder, since estimating encoder-side confidence is hard; this leads to suboptimal compute savings.","method":"MuE introduces dynamic early exiting in both encoder and decoder by using layer-wise input similarity as the exit signal. It measures cosine similarity of hidden states across layers to detect saturation; when similarity exceeds a threshold, subsequent layers are skipped. This multiple-exit mechanism applies per decoding step (with a decayed threshold for autoregressive generation) and achieves large speedups (e.g., up to ~50% expected time reduction on SNLI-VE and ~40% on COCO) with minimal performance drop."},{"problem":"Early-fusion encoders process image and text jointly, preventing modality-specific compute allocation even though modalities contribute unevenly across tasks (e.g., text is more critical for visual entailment, image for captioning).","method":"MuE decomposes the early-fusion encoder into modality-specific image and text encoders with tied weights (no extra parameters), processing modalities independently and allowing separate early exits per modality. The resulting representations are concatenated before decoding, enabling selective skipping of unnecessary modality layers and improving efficiency while preserving accuracy (e.g., fewer image layers suffice for visual entailment, whereas captioning needs more image layers)."},{"problem":"Early exiting can degrade performance because intermediate decoder states are not optimized to be predictive, and in generation tasks errors accumulate across timesteps.","method":"MuE adds a layer-wise task loss on every decoder layer during fine-tuning so that each layer is directly optimized for the end task, making intermediate representations more predictive and robust to early exit. Combined with a threshold decay schedule at early decoding steps, this mitigates error accumulation and narrows the performance gap versus full-depth inference, as validated by ablations and captioning metrics."}]}
